The paper deals with algorithms and complexity theory, specifically in the context of graph problems. The use of pairwise constraints and reductions to k-Clique and k-dominating set problems suggests a focus on computational complexity and graph theory, which are both covered by cs.DS and cs.CC. The mention of weighted and unweighted problems, as well as the search for a triangle of weight 0, suggests connections to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and computational geometry (cs.CG). Finally, the use of reductions and the focus on specific graph problems suggests connections to graph theory (cs.GT).
